            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>Macalister's claims of evidence of Christianisation of this ogham
                            stone are rightly argued against by <ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> 
                                    (<date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >56-7</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. <ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1991"
                                        >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">91,
                                    117</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> also points out that <q>genitive forms
                                often have the appearance of nominatives and Macalister was mislead
                                by this in the case of [this ogham stone], which he
                                described as a (Christian) `signature' as opposed to a (pagan)
                                `epitaph'. Here RONANN, MAQ and COMOGANN have the deceptive
                                appearance of nominatives but QRIMITIR with -IR, not -ER, is quite
                                clearly genitive</q>.
                    </p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p>The personal names RONANN and COMOGANN come from <hi rend="italic">rón
                    </hi> 'seal' and <hi rend="italic">com</hi>- `with' + <hi rend="italic">ag</hi> 'leads' 
                        (Gailsh <hi rend="italic">Comagus</hi>) (<ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">107</biblScope></bibl></ref>) 
                        and both ending with a late form of the diminutive suffix 
                        -<hi rend="italic">AN(N)</hi> (earlier -<hi rend="italic">AGNI</hi>).</p></item>
                    <item n="3"><p>In this inscription all endings are lost, including in the formula word 
                        (MAQ, earlier MAQ(Q)I) but syncope has not yet taken place. This linguistic evidnece 
                        suggests a date of approximately the <origDate notBefore="0550" notAfter="0600">second half of the sixth century</origDate> (<ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">96-7</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">the stone was found upright on <placeName type="findspot">Mt Brandon</placeName> but
                            buried in peat up to within 2 feet of the top (<ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                    <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >141</biblScope></bibl></ref>) in the townland of
                                <placeName type="townland">Arraglen</placeName> and barony of
                            <placeName type="barony">Corkaguiney</placeName>. (GPS coordinates <geo>-10.249772, 52.257546</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location probably original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">Re-erected in 1980s just a few meters from find spot (personal comment from Fionnbarr Moore) on <placeName type="findspot">Mount Brandon</placeName>.
                            The present location of this stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=KE025-002001-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                            www.archaeology.ie</ref>. </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
